Use the following thermochemical data to calculate the standard enthalpy of formation \( \Delta H_f^\circ \) for \( \mathrm{C_2H_6(g)} \):
\[ \begin{aligned} 
\mathrm{C_2H_6(g) + \frac{7}{2} O_2(g) &-> 2 CO_2(g) + 3 H_2O(l)} & \Delta H_1^\circ &= -1560 \text{ kJ/mol} \\
\mathrm{C(s) + O_2(g) &-> CO_2(g)} & \Delta H_2^\circ &= -393.5 \text{ kJ/mol} \\
\mathrm{H_2(g) + \frac{1}{2} O_2(g) &-> H_2O(l)} & \Delta H_3^\circ &= -285.8 \text{ kJ/mol} 
\end{aligned} \]

Given the following thermochemical equations:
1) \( \mathrm{C(s, graphite) + O_2(g) \rightarrow CO_2(g)} \quad \Delta H_1 = -393.5\text{ kJ}
2) \( \mathrm{C(s, diamond) + O_2(g) \rightarrow CO_2(g)} \quad \Delta H_2 = -395.4\text{ kJ}
3) \( \mathrm{C(s, graphite) \rightarrow C(s, diamond)} \quad \Delta H_3 = ?\)
What is the enthalpy change for the transition of graphite to diamond?

Given the following thermochemical equations:
1) \( \mathrm{C(s, graphite) + O_2(g) \rightarrow CO_2(g)} \quad \Delta H_1 = -393.5\text{ kJ}
2) \mathrm{C(s, diamond) + O_2(g) \rightarrow CO_2(g)} \quad \Delta H_2 = -395.7\text{ kJ}
What is the enthalpy change for the transition of graphite to diamond \( \mathrm{C(s, graphite) \rightarrow C(s, diamond)} \)?
